{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"feafaa3f-a490-4f67-be51-b8b77f361295","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for `.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS) files named after your process.\n\n**Quick way to find them:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\n**You can also use Console.app** → select \"Crash Reports\" in the sidebar.\n\nThese `.ips` files contain the native backtrace, which you can symbolicate using `atos` or the **apple-crash-symbolication** skill if you need to resolve .NET runtime frames to source code. Let me know if you'd like help with that!","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"20920691-4f36-4915-9149-a8d917af5e8c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question about macOS crash reporting mechanisms.","outputTokens":276,"requestId":"D802:2D8776:1CE21B:21DF5F:69F2B52F"},"id":"a1001f2b-853c-4e7c-b9cf-0dbe2a1f1449","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:49:42.912Z","parentId":"c96955a4-0614-4083-9572-470c6d7bd748"}
